user_query: What are the possible positions of the manual operator and what are the assiciated colors?
reference_answer: The possible positions of the manual operator are OFF (Green), TRIP, (Yellow), ON (Red), RESET (no color).
generated_answer:
The possible positions of the manual operator are:

1. Position OFF (O) - green marking
2. Position ON (I) - red marking
3. Position TRIP - yellow marking

The handle engages in one of these positions depending on the status of the molded case circuit breaker. The switching positions are color-coded so that you can identify the status of the circuit breaker at a glance.

user_query: What does it mean if the trip LED is off and the ACT led flashes in green?
generated_answer:
The image shows a motor operator control panel with various LEDs and switches. The trip LED is off, and the ACT LED is flashing in green.

In the context of this control panel, the trip LED typically indicates whether the motor is in a tripped or faulted state. If the trip LED is off, it means that the motor is not in a tripped state and is operating normally.

The ACT LED, on the other hand, is likely an indicator for the status of the motor operator. If the ACT LED is flashing in green, it could mean that the motor operator is in an active or operational state.

In summary, the off state of the trip LED and the green flashing state of the ACT LED suggest that the motor operator is currently operational and not in a tripped or faulted state.

user_query: How can I open the online help in the KUKA.HMI?
reference_answer: To open the online help, click on the "Help" button at the top right of the display
generated_answer:

1. In the main menu, select Help > Online Help.
2. The KUKA Embedded Information Service window will be opened.
3. Touch a chapter or topic to display the description.

Alternatively, you can also call the online help for a message that is currently displayed in the message window by touching the button containing the question mark. This will open the KUKA Embedded Information Service - Message page window, which contains a variety of information about the message, including the causes and solutions.

Calling context-sensitive online help 
 
1. 
You are in an arbitrary window of an operating area. 
 
 
 
2.

The help page of the currently selected window is opened in a sub-
screen. 
 
3. 
Press the "Full screen" softkey to use the entire user interface for the 
display of the online help.

4.3
Switching on the robot controller and starting the KSS
Procedure

Turn the main switch on the robot controller to ON.
The operating system and the KSS start automatically.
If the KSS does not start automatically, e.g. because the Startup function has 
been disabled, execute the file StartKRC.exe in the directory C:\KRC\BIN.
If the robot controller is logged onto the network, the start may take longer.
4.4
Restarting the KSS
Precondition

Operating mode T1 or T2.
Procedure
1.
Select the menu sequence File > Shut down KRC.
2.
Select the start type.
3.
Press the Shut Down softkey. Confirm the request for confirmation with 
Yes. 
The KSS is shut down and then automatically restarts immediately with the 
selected start type.
Description
Caution!
If the KSS has been restarted with the command Shut down KRC, the main 
switch on the robot controller must not be actuated during the rebooting se-
quence. System files may otherwise be destroyed.
If the robot controller detects a system error or modified data, the KSS always 
starts with a cold start – irrespective of the selected start type.
Fig. 4-15: Option window “Shut down KRC”
Item
Description
1
The next start is a cold start.

The next start is a warm start.

5
Start-up and recommissioning
5.1
Start-up wizard
Description
Start-up can be carried out using the Start-up wizard. This guides the user 
through the basic start-up steps.
Precondition

No program is selected.

Operating mode T1
Procedure

Select Start-up > Start-up wizard in the main menu.
5.2
Checking the machine data
Description
The correct machine data must be loaded. This must be checked by compar-
ing the loaded machine data with the machine data on the rating plate.
If machine data are reloaded, the version of the machine data must corre-
spond exactly to the KSS version. This is ensured if the machine data supplied 
together with the KSS release are used.
Precondition

T1 or T2 operating mode

No program is selected.
Procedure
1.
In the main menu, select Start-up > Robot data. 
The Robot Data window is opened.
2.
Compare the following entries:

In the Robot data window: the entry in the Machine data box

On the rating plate on the base of the robot: the entry in the line $TRA-
FONAME()=“# ..... ”
The industrial robot must not be moved if incorrect ma-
chine data are loaded. Death, severe injuries or consid-
erable damage to property may otherwise result. The correct machine data 
must be loaded.
Fig. 5-1: Rating plate

user_query: How can I restart the KSS?
reference_answer:
To restart the KSS, follow these steps:
1. Select the menu sequence File > Shut down KRC.
2. Select the start type. Available start types are Cold Boot, Warm Boot and Hibernate
3. Press the Shut Down softkey. Confirm the request for confirmation with Yes.
The KSS is shut down and then automatically restarts immediately with the selected start type.
generated_answer:
To restart the KSS, you can follow these steps:

1. Turn the main switch on the robot controller to ON.
2. If the KSS does not start automatically, execute the file StartKRC.exe in the directory C:\KRC\BIN.
3. Select the menu sequence File > Shut down KRC.
4. Select the start type.
5. Press the Shut Down softkey and confirm the request for confirmation with Yes.

Note: If the KSS has been restarted with the command Shut down KRC, the main switch on the robot controller must not be actuated during the rebooting sequence. System files may otherwise be destroyed.
